In algebra, a '''Weyl module''' is a [[group representation|representation]] of a [[reductive group|reductive]] [[algebraic group]], introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Carter||last2=Lusztig|year1=1974|year2=1974b}} and named after [[Hermann Weyl]]. In [[characteristic (algebra)|characteristic]]&nbsp;0 these representations are [[irreducible representation|irreducible]], but in positive characteristic they can be reducible, and their decomposition into irreducible components can be hard to determine.

